Exercise 1

We know from the previous exercises (walkthrough) that the area-under-the-curve (AUC) is related to the maximum absolute deviation (MAD). But what about reaction times (RTs)? Isnât it plausible that RTs are also related to AUC? The further I curve away from the target with the cursor, the longer it takes me to arrive at the target, right?

  1. Plot the relationship between RT and AUC in a scatterplot.
ggplot(data = dolphin_agg, aes(x = RT, y = AUC)) + 
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.3) +
  theme_aida()

  1. Run a linear regression using brms. AUC is the dependent variable (i.e.Â the measure) and RT is the independent variables (i.e.Â the predictor). The formula writes: AUC ~ RT
model1 = brm(formula = AUC ~ RT, data = dolphin_agg)
  1. Look at the model output. Think of it in terms of a line in the scatterplot from (1b). Where does the regression line cross the y-axis, what is the slope of the line? Draw a scatterplot of AUC against RT and add the predicted values as a line.
summary(model1)

Answer: The regression line crosses the y-axis at ~77185 (intercept) and the slope is -11.2, indicating a negative development of AUC scores with increasing RT value.

intercept = summary(model1)$fixed[1]
slope = summary(model1)$fixed[2]

ggplot(data = dolphin_agg, aes(x = RT, y = AUC)) + 
  geom_abline(aes(intercept = intercept, slope = slope), color = "black", size  = 1.5) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.3) +
  theme_aida()

That doesnât really look like what we have expected, right? If there is any relationship, AUC values become lower with longer reaction times (the line has a negative slope).

  1. Now create a new dataframe which contains the extracted posteriors for b_RT from the model output (use the spread_draws() function). Print out the head of the new dataset.
posteriors <- 
  model1 %>%
  spread_draws(b_RT) %>%
  select(b_RT) %>%
  gather(key = "parameter", value = "posterior")

head(posteriors)

  1. Plot the results with the `geom_halfeyeh() function. Add a vertical line at zero.
ggplot(posteriors, aes(x = posterior, y = parameter)) +
    geom_halfeyeh(.width = 0.95) +
    xlab("\nAUC") +
    ylab("") +
    #scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-100,600)) +
    geom_segment(x = 0, xend = 0, y = Inf, yend = -Inf, lty = "dashed")

Now: What is the evidence telling us? Is there compelling evidence for a relationship between AUC and RT? Think about it.

There is evidence for the relationship between AUC and RT, but it is weak at best. The value zero (no relationship) is contained in the 95% CrI and a non-trivial amount of posterior samples is larger than 0.

Try to understand the coefficient table. There is one coefficient for RT and one coefficient for correct which gives you the change in MAD from incorrect to correct responses.

  1. Plot a scatter plot of MAD ~ RT and color code it for correct responses (Tip: Make sure that correct is treated as a factor and not a numeric vector). Draw two predicted lines into the scatterplot. One for correct responses (âlightblueâ) and one for incorrect responses (âorangeâ).
intercept = summary(model2)$fixed[1]
slope = summary(model2)$fixed[2]
correct1 = summary(model2)$fixed[3]

ggplot(data = dolphin_agg, aes(x = RT, y = MAD, color = factor(correct))) + 
  geom_abline(aes(intercept = intercept + correct1, slope = slope), 
              color = "lightblue", size  = 1.5) +
  geom_abline(aes(intercept = intercept, slope = slope), color = "orange", size  = 1.5) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.3) +
  theme_aida() +
  theme(legend.position="none")

  1. Extract the posteriors for the coefficients of both RT and correct from the model output (use the spread_draws() function), calculate their means and a 67% Credible Interval. Print out the head of the aggregated dataframe.
coef_summary <-
  model2 %>%
  spread_draws(b_RT, b_correct) %>%
  select(b_RT, b_correct) %>% 
  gather(key = "parameter", value = "posterior") %>% 
  group_by(parameter) %>% 
  summarise(`67lowerCrI` = HDInterval::hdi(posterior, credMass = 0.67)[1],
            mean_posterior = mean(posterior),
            `67higherCrI` = HDInterval::hdi(posterior, credMass = 0.67)[2])

  1. BONUS I : Plot the scatterplot from 2c and plot 50 sample tuples for the regression lines for correct and incorrect responses.
get_variables(model2)
##  [1] "b_Intercept"   "b_RT"          "b_correct"     "sigma"

random_50 <- sample(1:4000, 50, replace = FALSE)

sample_tuples <- model2 %>%
  spread_draws(b_RT, b_Intercept, b_correct) %>%
  select(b_RT, b_Intercept, b_correct) %>% 
  slice(random_50)

ggplot(data = dolphin_agg, aes(x = RT, y = MAD, color = factor(correct))) + 
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_abline(data = sample_tuples, 
              aes(intercept = b_Intercept + b_correct, slope = b_RT, color = "lightblue"),
              size = 0.15, alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_abline(data = sample_tuples, aes(intercept = b_Intercept, slope = b_RT, color = "orange"),
              size = 0.15, alpha = 0.3) +
  theme_aida() +
  theme(legend.position="none")

  1. BONUS II: Given our model and our data, calculate the evidential ratio of correct responses exhibiting larger MADs than incorrect responses.
hypothesis(model2, hypothesis = "Intercept + RT + correct > Intercept + RT")

##   Post.Prob Star

Answer: The hypothesis test suggests a posterior probability of 0.29 for the event that correct responses exhibit larger MADs than incorrect responses. This in turn results in an evidence ratio of ~ 0.4 (0.28 / (1-0.28)).
